Key words:


Chartergus


; 
Epiponini
; 
Marimbondo
; 
swarm-founding
; 
paper wasps

The complete list of specimens used in our phylogenetic analyses is presented in Supplementary Material (Table S1). We used Cytochrome c oxidase I (COI) sequences extracted from off-target sequences of ultraconserved elements raw sequencing data (for details see
Menezes et al . 2023
). The COI is a good mitochondrial marker for systematic investigations in social wasps (
Menezes et al . 2023
). We performed the alignment using the MAFFT v7.0 algorithm (
Katoh et al . 2019
), available on the MAFFT webserver (https://mafft.cbrc.jp/alignment/server/), employing the GINS-i strategy and default settings. We visually inspected and corrected all alignments. The most suitable model of nucleotide evolution by codon position for COI was determined using PARTITIONFINDER2 (
Lanfear et al . 2016
) under the Bayesian information criterion. Subsequently, we concatenated the COI and morphological characters using the software MESQUITE v.3.61 ( Maddison & Maddison 2019 ).

In our phylogenetic analyses, we included
Protonectarina sylveirae (de Saussure, 1854)
,
Brachygastra lecheguana (Latreille, 1804)
, and
Protopolybia bituberculata Silveira & Carpenter, 1996
, as outgroup taxa based on previous phylogenetic studies (
Menezes et al . 2020
, 2023 ;
Noll et al . 2021
). We performed phylogenetic analyses using a combined dataset of morphological and molecular data, employing Maximum Parsimony (MP) and Maximum Likelihood (ML) methods. For MP analysis, we used TNT version 1.5 (
Goloboff et al . 2008
) and conducted tree search with Implicit Enumeration. Clade support was assessed using Symmetric Resampling for MP (
Goloboff et al . 2003
). For ML analysis, we used IQ-TREE v.2.2.2.6 (
Minh et al . 2020
) and calculated branch supports with 1000 replicates of the Shimodaira-Hasegawa approximate likelihood ratio test (SH-aLRT) (
Guindon et al . 2010
) and parametric ultrafast bootstrap (UFBoot2) (
Hoang et al . 2018
).

